Document: how_to_read_the_godot_api
Path: godot/tutorials/scripting/how_to_read_the_godot_api.rst
Summary: Explains how to navigate and understand the Godot API class reference documentation.

The API, or Application Programming Interface, is an index of what Godot offers users. It provides a brief summary of which classes exist, how they are related to each other, what features they have, and how to use them. This page teaches how to read the class reference for the Godot API, which serves as a central resource for understanding the structure and functionality of Godot's programming interface. The documentation organizes classes hierarchically, showing inheritance relationships and detailing each class's methods, properties, signals, and constants. It also includes usage examples, parameter descriptions, and return value information to help developers implement features effectively.
---CHUNK---
Document: how_to_read_the_godot_api
Path: godot/tutorials/scripting/how_to_read_the_godot_api.rst
Summary: Explains how to interpret inheritance relationships in Godot's API documentation

At the top of each file, you will see the name of the class. The "Inherits" section lists each class the current one inherits. Here CanvasItem inherits Node and Node inherits Object. The "Inherited By" section lists each class which directly inherits the current class. Here Control and Node2D both inherit CanvasItem.
---CHUNK---
Document: how_to_read_the_godot_api
Path: godot/tutorials/scripting/how_to_read_the_godot_api.rst
Summary: Explains how brief class descriptions are used in Godot Editor popups for node and resource creation.

Brief Description. Next a brief description of the class. This text appears in Godot Editor popups for creating Nodes, Resources, and other types.
