Document: how_to_read_the_godot_api  
Path: godot/tutorials/scripting/how_to_read_the_godot_api.rst  
Summary: Explains the structure and purpose of the Properties table in Godot's API documentation.  

The Properties table lists variables belonging to each instance of a class, also known as "properties." The left column shows the data type of the property, with text linked to the corresponding data type's Godot API page. The center column displays the property name, linked to its full description on the page. This name is used to access or modify the property's value. The right column indicates the default value of the property. To initialize a property with a different value, set it via script or the Inspector.
---CHUNK---
Document: how_to_read_the_godot_api
Path: godot/tutorials/scripting/how_to_read_the_godot_api.rst
Summary: Explains how to interpret the Methods table in Godot's API documentation, including return types, parameters, and method qualifiers.

The Methods table lists functions belonging to each class instance. The left column shows the return value's data type. The right column contains method names, parameters, and qualifiers. Method names link to full descriptions and are used to call the method. Each parameter's data type, name, and default value are detailed. Possible qualifiers include: const (method does not modify class data), virtual (method waits for script override), and vararg (method accepts arbitrary arguments).
---CHUNK---
Document: how_to_read_the_godot_api
Path: godot/tutorials/scripting/how_to_read_the_godot_api.rst
Summary: Explains how to interpret the Signals section in the Godot API, detailing event names, parameters, and their emission contexts.

Signals list details the names and parameters of events which "signal" a change in game state to other class instances. Like the Methods table, any parameters will include their data type and name. Each signal also has a detailed explanation of when the signal is emitted.
---CHUNK---
Document: how_to_read_the_godot_api
Path: godot/tutorials/scripting/how_to_read_the_godot_api.rst
Summary: Explains how Godot's API documentation details enumerations and their associated values for a class.

The Enumerations list details the enumerable data types associated with the current class. For each enumeration, the page states its name and then lists its possible values. For each enumeration value, the page states its name, its integer value, and an explanation of its use case(s) and/or affects. This structure allows developers to quickly reference available options and understand their functional implications when working with the class's API.
---CHUNK---
Document: how_to_read_the_godot_api
Path: godot/tutorials/scripting/how_to_read_the_godot_api.rst
Summary: Explains how to interpret the Constants section in Godot's API documentation, including named integer values and their use cases.

The Constants list details named integer constants in the current class. For each constant, the page states its name, its integer value, and an explanation of its use case(s) and/or affects. ``NOTIFICATION_*`` constants' descriptions will state which engine event triggers the notification.
---CHUNK---
Document: how_to_read_the_godot_api
Path: godot/tutorials/scripting/how_to_read_the_godot_api.rst
Summary: Explains how the Property Descriptions list in Godot's API documentation details property data types, setter/getter functions, and usage context.

The Property Descriptions list details everything about each property. It restates the data type and name of the property. Every property in the Godot API is bound to a pair of setter and getter functions. Using either is equivalent. They are listed here. Below that is a detailed summary of what the property's data represents, its use case(s), and/or the affects of changing it. It may include code samples and/or links to relevant parts of the Godot API. Note: Knowing the setter and getter names is useful when one must bind a method name or Callable to something.
---CHUNK---
Document: how_to_read_the_godot_api
Path: godot/tutorials/scripting/how_to_read_the_godot_api.rst
Summary: This section explains how to interpret method descriptions in the Godot API, including return types, parameters, and usage details.

Method Descriptions list details everything about each method. It restates the method's return data type, parameter names/types/defaults, and qualifiers. Below that is a detailed summary of what the method does and its use case(s). It may include code samples and/or links to relevant parts of the Godot API.